\"font-style:italic;\">Physcomitrium acutifolium<\/span><span>, and<\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">Physcomitrella patens<\/span><span>. All moss species underwent 12 h and 24 h treatment with salt at different concentrations, followed by qRT-PCR experiments.<\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><span>In <\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">F. hygrometrica<\/span><span>, the MBF1c gene was up-regulated when subjected to 12 h salt treatment at a medium concentration, and may be an important factor for the tolerance of plants to NaCl concentrations. In<\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">P. acutifolium,<\/span><span>24 h NaCl treatment at of 400, 600, and 800 mM resulted in a gradual up-regulation of MBF1c expression, reflective of the increasing NaCl concentration. In<\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">Physcomitrella,<\/span><span>the expression profile of MBF1c showed a down-regulation when treated with 200, 400, and 800 mM NaCl, suggesting that MBF1c may not interfere with the saline stress response in this plant.<\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\">The diversity of these expression profiles demonstrate that the MBF1c response is not universal neither among plants nor between species of the same family, as shown in the mosses studied.<\/div><\/div>","changed_on":1586856105}